Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Meanwhile, drain the @Halloumi{225%grams}, then cut it in half lengthways to make 2 'steaks', 1 per person. Place them into a #medium bowl{} of cold water and leave to soak.

Meanwhile, chop the @Potatoes{450%grams} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop the wedges onto a #large baking tray{}. Drizzle with oil, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, in a #large bowl{}, combine the @Cider Vinegar{15%milliliter(s)}, @Sugar{1%tsp} and @Olive Oil{1%tbsp} for the dressing. Halve the @Baby Plum Tomatoes{125%grams} and add to the dressing. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and set aside for now.

About ~{15%minutes} before the wedges are ready, remove the halloumi steaks from the water, pop them onto a #plate{} lined with #kitchen paper{} and pat them dry. Sprinkle over the @Central American Style Spice Mix{1%sachet}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the halloumi and fry until golden, ~{2-3%minutes} each side.

Transfer the halloumi to a #medium baking tray{} and bake on the middle shelf of your oven until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

While everything cooks, clean out the (now empty) #frying pan{} and pop it back on medium heat. Add the @Hot Sauce{30%grams}, @Honey{15%grams} and @Butter{30%grams} and stir vigorously until the butter has melted and the sauce is piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, put the sachet in a #bowl{} of hot water for ~{1%minute} to loosen.

When everything's ready, add the @Baby Leaf Mix{50%grams} to the #bowl{} of tomatoes and toss together.

Share the halloumi steaks out between your #plates{}, spooning over the hot honey sauce (reheat first if needed). Serve the wedges, salad and a dollop of the @Mayonnaise{1%tbsp} alongside. Enjoy!